<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|1|32:1">
<para.text>
A &ldquo;“cooperative corporation&rdquo;” is an organization created by the banding together of persons for their common advantage or advancement, financial or otherwise, and is organized for the mutual benefit of its members, without gain to itself.<footnote><footnote.reference>1</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|1|32:1"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047FTH"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§13.Research References►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04A8YD"</f_field>Monopolies: construction of sec. 1 of the Capper-Volstead Act (7 U.S.C.A. sec. 291) authorizing persons engaged in the production of agricultural products to act together in association, 20 A.L.R. Fed. 924.Cooperative corporations, generally, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D239"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§6159, 602.Definition and nature of cooperative associations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I047FUM"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§1.</footnote.body></footnote> The most common type of cooperative corporation is the nonprofit agricultural cooperative corporation and the New York statutes expressly provide for the organization of such corporations.<footnote><footnote.reference>2</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|1|32:1"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04A8ZI"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§110 et seq.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I047FUP"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|1|32:1">
<para.text>
Cooperative corporations are distinguished from other business structures by the features of democratic control and voting, the distribution of economic benefits on an equal basis or in proportion to the use made of the corporation facilities, limited return on capital, and the fact that most of the cooperative's business is done with its own members.<footnote><footnote.reference>3</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|1|32:1"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047G0C"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§14 for a list of the general powers of a cooperative corporation.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04A958"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.Distinctive features of cooperative associations. ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D2A4"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§2.</footnote.body></footnote> It should be noted that federal legislation authorizing associations of agricultural producers applies only to corporations that, inter alia, allow only one vote per member, or that do not pay dividends on stock or membership capital in excess of 12&percnt;% per year. The New York statute establishes these criteria.<footnote><footnote.reference>4</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|1|32:1"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047G0H"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§44, 111.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D2A9"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.Voting by members of cooperative associations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FVF5"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§9168.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
</section>
