<section>
<section.front>
<outline.name.block>
<designator>32:2</designator>
<name>General background</name>
</outline.name.block>
<research.reference.block>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I047G0K"</field>West's Key Number Digest, Agriculture &key;6</ref.text></reference.entry>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I04A95G"</field>West's Key Number Digest, <trace.deleted>Associations &key;1</trace.deleted><trace>Associations &key;101</trace> et seq.</ref.text></reference.entry>
</research.reference.block>
</section.front>
<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2">
<para.text>
Agricultural cooperative corporations are governed by the provisions of the New York Cooperative Corporations Law, specifically ►<field>st.ref.id="I04D2AC"</field>Sections 110 to 113. Under these statutes, any five or more producers of agricultural products may form a nonprofit, cooperative agricultural corporation, with or without stock, by subscribing and filing a certificate of incorporation.<footnote><footnote.reference>5</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047G1P"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§112.Research ReferencesSpecific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04A96L"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.Purposes of agricultural cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D2BH"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§613, 624.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2">
<para.text>
The New York Business Corporation Law also applies in areas that are not directly addressed by the Cooperative Corporations Law, with certain exceptions that are delineated in ►<field>st.ref.id="I04FVGD"</field>Section 5 of the Cooperative Corporations Law. Organizations operating under this type of statutory provision are generally exempt from prosecution for certain actions that might otherwise be considered as being in restraint of trade.<footnote><footnote.reference>6</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>Research ReferencesApplication of business corporation law to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05S5C0"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§5.Agricultural cooperatives and antitrust laws, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05PC74"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Monopolies, Restraints of Trade, and Unfair Trade Practices &ss;§§2259 to 22933.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2">
<para.text>
Cooperative corporations are deemed to be nonprofit corporations, inasmuch as their primary objective is not to make profits or to pay dividends on invested capital, but to provide service, whereby the members may have the economic advantage of cooperative action, which includes a reasonable return for their product and service.<footnote><footnote.reference>7</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05S5BY"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§3(d).</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2">
<para.text>
Cooperative corporations are generally organized to secure for their members the advantages of cooperative bargaining in selling their products, marketing such products, and turning back to the members or other producers the proceeds of sales, less the necessary marketing expenses.<footnote><footnote.reference>8</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05PC72"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§13 and 110 for a comprehensive statement of the purposes for organizing a cooperative corporation.Research References►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05S56B"</f_field>Construction and application of provision in Robinson-Patman Act (15 USC sec. 13c) exempting nonprofit institutions from price discrimination provision of the Act, 3 A.L.R. Fed. 996.For a discussion of cooperative corporations, generally, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05S568"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§6159.Purposes of cooperative associations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05PC1C"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§4.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2">
<para.text>
Other types of cooperatives authorized by statute in New York, but not treated to any extent in this article, are worker cooperative corporations,<footnote><footnote.reference>9</footnote.reference><footnote.body>5►<f_field>fn.fnref="5"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05MIWG"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§80 to 94.Research ReferencesWorker cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05S566"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§332.</footnote.body></footnote> cooperative credit corporations,<footnote><footnote.reference>10</footnote.reference><footnote.body>6►<f_field>fn.fnref="6"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05PC1A"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§120 to 123.Research ReferencesAgency and credit cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05MIWE"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§310.</footnote.body></footnote> and cooperatives for the purpose of providing electrical power to rural areas.<footnote><footnote.reference>11</footnote.reference><footnote.body>7►<f_field>fn.fnref="7"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05S563"</f_field>Rural Elec. Coop. Law &ss;§§1 to 72; ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05PC17"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§76.Research ReferencesRural electric cooperatives, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05MIWB"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§321.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2">
<para.text>
Cooperative corporations organized under the laws of other states or any foreign corporation that has as its purpose or among its purposes the cooperative rendering of mutual support to its members may, in furtherance of its cooperative objectives, do business in New York and make and enforce contracts in the state upon compliance with the provisions of the New York Cooperative Corporations Law and with other laws applicable to foreign corporations.<footnote><footnote.reference>12</footnote.reference><footnote.body>8►<f_field>fn.fnref="8"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05JPRF"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§76.Research ReferencesForeign cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I047G8U"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§646.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2">
<para.text>
In addition to the powers specified in the Cooperative Corporations Law, cooperative corporations possess the powers and rights set out in the Business Corporation Law and the N.Y. Not-for-Profit Corporation Law subject to the provisions of the Cooperative Corporations Law.<footnote><footnote.reference>13</footnote.reference><footnote.body>9►<f_field>fn.fnref="9"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|2|32:2"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04A9DQ"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§14.Research ReferencesPowers of cooperative corporations, generally, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I047G8X"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§4723 to 4776.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
