<section.front>
<outline.name.block>
<designator>32:8</designator>
<name>Introduction</name>
</outline.name.block>
<research.reference.block>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I04AAC5"</field>West's Key Number Digest, Agriculture &key;6</ref.text></reference.entry>
</research.reference.block>
</section.front>
<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8">
<para.text>
A nonprofit cooperative agricultural corporation may be organized to engage in any cooperative activities for its members, including the marketing, selling of, bargaining, and contracting for agricultural products and the by-products of such products.<footnote><footnote.reference>53</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047H8F"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§110, 112.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D3I7"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.Purposes of agricultural cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FWN3"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§6361.Specific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04IPRZ"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.Purposes of cooperative associations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04LIWV"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§4.</footnote.body></footnote> Any five or more producers of agricultural products, to include cooperative corporations of such producers organized under the laws of New York or any other state, may form a nonprofit cooperative agricultural corporation, either with or without capital stock.<footnote><footnote.reference>54</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047H8H"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§111, 112.Research ReferencesSpecific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I047HE5"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8">
<para.text>
If the principal activities of the corporation are connected with the marketing, processing, manufacture, or sale of agricultural products, it may be termed a cooperative agricultural corporation and incorporated as such.<footnote><footnote.reference>55</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04AAJ1"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§111, 112.</footnote.body></footnote> If its principal activities relate to the purchase of supplies for producers of agricultural products, it may be termed a cooperative purchasing association and may be incorporated as such.<footnote><footnote.reference>56</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04FWST"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§112.</footnote.body></footnote> In either case, the corporation may engage in both types of activity.<footnote><footnote.reference>57</footnote.reference><footnote.body>5►<f_field>fn.fnref="5"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04IPXP"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§112.</footnote.body></footnote> A nonprofit agricultural cooperative association of this nature may be incorporated with or without capital stock.<footnote><footnote.reference>58</footnote.reference><footnote.body>6►<f_field>fn.fnref="6"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04LJ2L"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§112.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8">
<para.text>
The amount of dividends that may be declared on stock cannot exceed 12&percnt;% per year.<footnote><footnote.reference>59</footnote.reference><footnote.body>7►<f_field>fn.fnref="7"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047HE7"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§111.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AAJ3"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8">
<para.text>
The exempt income tax status of farmers' cooperatives is extended even though they have capital stock if the dividend rate of the stock is fixed at a rate not to exceed the legal rate of interest in the state of incorporation or 8&percnt;% per year, whichever is greater, on the value of the consideration for which the stock was issued and if substantially all such stock (other than nonvoting preferred stock, the owners of which are not entitled or permitted to participate, directly or indirectly, in the profits of the association, on dissolution or otherwise, beyond the fixed dividends) is owned by producers who market their products or purchase their supplies and equipment through the association.<footnote><footnote.reference>60</footnote.reference><footnote.body>8►<f_field>fn.fnref="8"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04D3NZ"</f_field>26 U.S.C.A. &s;§521(b)(2).Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FWSV"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8">
<para.text>
Transactions with nonmembers will not bar a farmers' cooperative from claiming an exempt status under the federal income tax laws, provided the value of the transactions, in relation to those with members, does not exceed statutory limits.<footnote><footnote.reference>61</footnote.reference><footnote.body>9►<f_field>fn.fnref="9"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047HEA"</f_field>26 U.S.C.A. &s;§521(b)(4).</footnote.body></footnote> An exemption will not be denied any association that markets the products of nonmembers in an amount the value of which does not exceed the value of the products marketed for members or which purchases supplies and equipment for nonmembers in an amount the value of which does not exceed the value of the supplies and equipment purchased for members, provided the value of the purchases made for persons who are neither members nor producers does not exceed 15&percnt;% of the value of all purchases.1<footnote><footnote.reference>62</footnote.reference><footnote.body>10►<f_field>fn.fnref="10"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04AAJ6"</f_field>26 U.S.C.A. &s;§521(b)(4).</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8">
<para.text>
Business done for the United States or any of its agencies is disregarded in determining the right to exemption.1<footnote><footnote.reference>63</footnote.reference><footnote.body>11►<f_field>fn.fnref="11"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047HEC"</f_field>26 U.S.C.A. &s;§521(b)(5).</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8">
<para.text>
The provisions of the Business Corporation Law of New York and all powers and rights conferred under such law apply to agricultural cooperative corporations except where such provisions are in conflict with or are inconsistent with the express provisions of the Agricultural Cooperative Corporations Law.1<footnote><footnote.reference>64</footnote.reference><footnote.body>12►<f_field>fn.fnref="12"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|8|32:8"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04AAJ8"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§5.Research ReferencesApplication of business corporation law to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D3O4"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§5 to 7.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
</section>
<analytical.level.body>
<section.block>
<section>
<section.front>
<outline.name.block>
<designator>32:9</designator>
<name>Drafting preorganization agreements and certificates of incorporation</name>
</outline.name.block>
<research.reference.block>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I047HFH"</field>West's Key Number Digest, Agriculture &key;6</ref.text></reference.entry>
</research.reference.block>
</section.front>
<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9">
<para.text>
In drafting the organization agreement, also commonly known as the preorganization agreement, the general policies of promoting the cultivation and marketing of agricultural products through cooperation and of distributing the agricultural products in as direct a manner as possible between the producer and the consumer should be stated.<footnote><footnote.reference>65</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04AAKD"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§110.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D3P9"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.Specific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FWU5"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9">
<para.text>
It is the declared policy of the state of New York to promote the effective production and merchandising of agricultural commodities by providing the means by which farmers may act together in manufacturing, processing, preparing for market, handling and/or marketing their farm products and by enabling farmers to act together in purchasing, testing, grading, processing, distributing and/or furnishing farm supplies and/or farm business services through cooperatives operated for the mutual benefit of the members of the corporations as producers and purchasers.<footnote><footnote.reference>66</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047HFK"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§110.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AAKG"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.Specific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D3PC"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
<online.view.item>Practice Tip:</online.view.item>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9">
<para.text>
As eventually drawn, the agreement should bind the producer to belong to and patronize the proposed cooperative and to furnish the specified amount of initial capital, contingent on the signing up of a sufficient number of other prospective members within a given time period. The chief provisions proposed for the bylaws should be indicated and the form of the marketing agreement to be used should be set forth.
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9">
<para.text>
New York statutory law specifies the matters required to be included in the certificate of incorporation of a cooperative corporation.<footnote><footnote.reference>67</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04FWU8"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§11.Research ReferencesSpecific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I047HFM"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.</footnote.body></footnote> These requirements are set out in a subsequent checklist.<footnote><footnote.reference>68</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>See ►<f_field>x.ref.id="I05S3SI"</f_field>&s;§32:12.</footnote.body></footnote> The certificate should specify that the organization will deal only in agricultural products, as defined in ►<field>st.ref.id="I05PANM"</field>Sections 110 to 113 of the New York Cooperative Corporations Law,<footnote><footnote.reference>69</footnote.reference><footnote.body>5►<f_field>fn.fnref="5"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05MHIQ"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &ss;§§3(a), 111(b).</footnote.body></footnote> and should make clear that the organization will qualify as an agricultural cooperative within the meaning of the statute.<footnote><footnote.reference>70</footnote.reference><footnote.body>6►<f_field>fn.fnref="6"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05GV8Y"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§111(a).Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05E242"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.Specific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05S3SG"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.</footnote.body></footnote> &ldquo;“Agricultural product&rdquo;” is defined as any product of cultivating land, and includes floricultural, horticultural, viticultural, forestry, nut, dairy, livestock, poultry, bee, and any farm products or by-products thereof.<footnote><footnote.reference>71</footnote.reference><footnote.body>7►<f_field>fn.fnref="7"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05PANK"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§3(a).</footnote.body></footnote> An &ldquo;“agricultural cooperative&rdquo;” is a cooperative, either stock or nonstock, operated for the mutual benefit of the members in which no member is allowed more than one vote because of the amount of stock or membership capital he or she may own therein; the cooperative does not pay dividends on stock or membership capital in excess of 12&percnt;% per year; and the cooperative does not deal in farm products, agricultural waste products or agricultural compost, farm supplies, farm business services and the capture of methane and other gases for the generation and use or sale of energy, with or for nonmembers in an amount greater in value than the total amount of such business transacted by it with or for members.<footnote><footnote.reference>72</footnote.reference><footnote.body>8►<f_field>fn.fnref="8"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05MHIO"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§111(a).►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>Question of whether cooperative is &ldquo;“agricultural cooperative corporation&rdquo;” within meaning of Agriculture and Markets Law is resolved solely by reference to statutory definition contained in Cooperative Corporations Law. ►<f_field>cc.ref.id="I05JODS"</f_field>Atwater v. McGuire, 227 A.D.2d 763, 642 N.Y.S.2d 363 (3d Dep't 1996).</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
<online.view.item>Practice Tips:</online.view.item>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9">
<para.text>
Because the certificate of incorporation of an agricultural cooperative association is generally more difficult to amend than its bylaws,<footnote><footnote.reference>73</footnote.reference><footnote.body>9►<f_field>fn.fnref="9"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>For requirements to amend certificates, see ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05S3SD"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§12.Research ReferencesAmendment or repeal of bylaws of cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05PANH"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§130§128.Amending certificate of incorporation of cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05MHIL"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§162158.</footnote.body></footnote> it is recommended that the substantive content of the certificate be limited to the statutory requirements.1<footnote><footnote.reference>74</footnote.reference><footnote.body>10►<f_field>fn.fnref="10"</f_field>Research References►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05JODP"</f_field>Construction and effect of corporate bylaws or articles relating to change in number of directors, 3 A.L.R.3d 623.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9">
<para.text>
In general, the provisions of the New York Business Corporation Law applies to agricultural cooperative corporations except where such provisions are in conflict with or are inconsistent with the particular provisions applicable to cooperatives.1<footnote><footnote.reference>75</footnote.reference><footnote.body>11►<f_field>fn.fnref="11"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05S3SB"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§5.►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|9|32:9"</f_field>For forms and materials appropriate for use under the New York Business Corporation Law, see ►<f_field>x.ref.id="I05PANF"</f_field>&ss;§§17:1 et seq.Research ReferencesApplication of business corporation law to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05S3R6"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§5 to 7.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
</section>
<analytical.level.body>
<section.block>
<section>
<section.front>
<outline.name.block>
<designator>32:10</designator>
<name>Drafting certificate of incorporation; formal requirements</name>
</outline.name.block>
<research.reference.block>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I05PAMA"</field>West's Key Number Digest, Agriculture &key;6</ref.text></reference.entry>
</research.reference.block>
</section.front>
<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10">
<para.text>
The certificate of incorporation must be made, acknowledged, and filed by five or more persons.<footnote><footnote.reference>76</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05MHHE"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§11.►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>A corporation's existence commences upon the filing of a certificate of incorporation with the Department of State. ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05JOCI"</f_field>BCL &s;§403. The certificate is conclusive evidence that all conditions precedent have been fulfilled and that the corporation has been formed under the appropriate statute. ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05GV7M"</f_field>BCL &s;§403.Research ReferencesSpecific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05S3R3"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.Evidentiary effect of certificate, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05PAM7"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§835.Commencement of corporate existence, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05MHHB"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§10911.</footnote.body></footnote> All the subscribers must be of full age, at least two-thirds of them must be citizens of the United States and at least one of them must be a resident of the State of New York and, of the persons named as directors at least one must be a citizen of the United States and a resident of the State of New York.<footnote><footnote.reference>77</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05JOCF"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§11(9).Research ReferencesSpecific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I05GV7J"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§753.</footnote.body></footnote> It may contain any provision, not inconsistent with the law, that the incorporators elect to set forth for the regulation of the internal affairs of the corporation.<footnote><footnote.reference>78</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047PHO"</f_field>BCL &s;§402(c).</footnote.body></footnote> The general requirements for a certificate of incorporation to be filed by a cooperative corporation are set out in the Cooperative Corporations Law.<footnote><footnote.reference>79</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04AIMK"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§11.Research ReferencesSpecific requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04DBRG"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§735.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10">
<para.text>
To assist in the processing of documents that are to be filed in the office of the Department of State, the physical appearance and makeup of such documents, including certificates of incorporation, should be in good legal form and be clearly legible.<footnote><footnote.reference>80</footnote.reference><footnote.body>5►<f_field>fn.fnref="5"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047PHR"</f_field>19 NYCRR &s;§150.2; ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04AIMN"</f_field>BCL &s;§104.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
<online.view.item>Practice Tip:</online.view.item>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10">
<para.text>
It is recommended that you check with the Secretary of State's office with regard to the form, filing, and information necessary for the return of the filed certificate.
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10">
<para.text>
The directors are required periodically to set aside reasonable sums for reserves.<footnote><footnote.reference>81</footnote.reference><footnote.body>6►<f_field>fn.fnref="6"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047PHT"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§72.Research ReferencesPower of cooperative corporations to establish reserves, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AIMP"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§476§475.</footnote.body></footnote> The net margins or net retained proceeds may, in the discretion of the directors, be distributed at least once a year to members or patrons by uniform distribution and calculated on such basis as the bylaws or marketing contract may prescribe.<footnote><footnote.reference>82</footnote.reference><footnote.body>7►<f_field>fn.fnref="7"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04DBRL"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§72.Research References►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04G4WH"</f_field>Co-operative associations: rights in equity credits or patronage dividends, 50 A.L.R.3d 435.Power of cooperative corporations to establish reserves, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04IY1D"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§476§475.</footnote.body></footnote> Distributions may be credited on account of the issuance to members or patrons of capital stock or other securities of the corporation.<footnote><footnote.reference>83</footnote.reference><footnote.body>8►<f_field>fn.fnref="8"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047PHW"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§72.Research References►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AIMS"</f_field>Co-operative associations: rights in equity credits or patronage dividends, 50 A.L.R.3d 435.Power of cooperative corporations to establish reserves, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04DBRO"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§476§475.</footnote.body></footnote> In the case of cooperatives with capital stock, dividends may not exceed 12&percnt;% per year on any class of stock.<footnote><footnote.reference>84</footnote.reference><footnote.body>9►<f_field>fn.fnref="9"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04G4WK"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§72. See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04IY1G"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§111.Research References►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I047PJ1"</f_field>Co-operative associations: rights in equity credits or patronage dividends, 50 A.L.R.3d 435.Power of cooperative corporations to establish reserves, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AINX"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§476§475.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10">
<para.text>
A certificate of incorporation or amendment of such certificate will not take effect until it has been filed with the Secretary of State.1<footnote><footnote.reference>85</footnote.reference><footnote.body>10►<f_field>fn.fnref="10"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04DBST"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§15.Research ReferencesAmending certificate of incorporation of cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04G4XP"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§162158.</footnote.body></footnote> The Secretary of State will provide copies of the certificates or amendments to the Commissioner of Agriculture and Markets or his or her designee on request by corporation name.1<footnote><footnote.reference>86</footnote.reference><footnote.body>11►<f_field>fn.fnref="11"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|10|32:10"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047PJ4"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§15.Research ReferencesAdditional requirements pertaining to cooperative corporations, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AIO0"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§802.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
</section>
