<section.block>
<section>
<section.front>
<outline.name.block>
<designator>32:11</designator>
<name>Drafting bylaws</name>
</outline.name.block>
<research.reference.block>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I047PJ6"</field>West's Key Number Digest, Agriculture &key;6</ref.text></reference.entry>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I04AIO2"</field>West's Key Number Digest, <trace.deleted>Associations &key;5</trace.deleted><trace>Associations &key;128, 129</trace></ref.text></reference.entry>
</research.reference.block>
</section.front>
<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11">
<para.text>
The New York Statutes require that bylaws regulating the conduct and manner of the corporation be adopted by its incorporators at the organization meeting.<footnote><footnote.reference>87</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04DBSY"</f_field>BCL &s;§601(a).Research ReferencesPower of cooperative corporations to adopt bylaws, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04G4XU"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§121119.</footnote.body></footnote> Thereafter, bylaws may be adopted by vote of the holders of the shares at the time entitled to vote in the election of any directors.<footnote><footnote.reference>88</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04IY2Q"</f_field>BCL &s;§601(a).</footnote.body></footnote> When so provided in the certificate of incorporation or a bylaw adopted by the shareholders, bylaws may also be adopted by the board of directors.<footnote><footnote.reference>89</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047POT"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§16.Research References►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AITP"</f_field>Co-operative associations: validity and enforceability of by-law amendment reducing benefits available to members, 61 A.L.R.3d 976.►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04DBYL"</f_field>Co-operative associations: rights in equity credits or patronage dividends, 50 A.L.R.3d 435.For a discussion of bylaws, see ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04G53H"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§1168 to 12931.Power of cooperative corporations to establish reserves, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04IY8D"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§476§475.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11">
<para.text>
Any bylaw adopted by the board of directors must be reported to the annual meeting of the corporation and, if not affirmatively approved at such meeting, will cease to be in effect.<footnote><footnote.reference>90</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047POW"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§16.</footnote.body></footnote> A listing of the matters authorized by statute to be included in the bylaws of an agricultural cooperative association is set out in a subsequent checklist.<footnote><footnote.reference>91</footnote.reference><footnote.body>5►<f_field>fn.fnref="5"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11"</f_field>See ►<f_field>x.ref.id="I04AITS"</f_field>&s;§32:13.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11">
<para.text>
In many respects, the bylaws of an agricultural cooperative resemble those of a business corporation.<footnote><footnote.reference>92</footnote.reference><footnote.body>6►<f_field>fn.fnref="6"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11"</f_field>For forms and discussion relating to corporate bylaws, see ►<f_field>x.ref.id="I04DBYO"</f_field>&ss;§§17:1 et seq.</footnote.body></footnote> However, there are several notable differences. For example, the bylaws of an agricultural marketing cooperative are often tied to a marketing agreement between the cooperative and its members. The bylaws frequently incorporate the agreement by reference and may specify the method to be used to create, accumulate, and maintain the reserves required by statute.<footnote><footnote.reference>93</footnote.reference><footnote.body>7►<f_field>fn.fnref="7"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|11|32:11"</f_field>See, generally, ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I047POY"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§113.Research ReferencesPower of cooperative corporations to establish reserves, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04AITU"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§476§475.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
</section>
</analytical.level>
</analytical.level.body>
