<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48">
<para.text>
In New York, specific statutory provisions authorize marketing contracts between a cooperative corporation and its members, under which the members are required to sell all or any specified portion of any product or specified commodity exclusively to or through the corporation or facilities created by the corporation.<footnote><footnote.reference>94</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05MIWF"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(1).</footnote.body></footnote> Such contracts may obligate the members during any designated period of time, subject to the right of each member to be released at a designated period in each year, by giving a prescribed notice.<footnote><footnote.reference>95</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05JPRJ"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(1).</footnote.body></footnote> These contracts are expressly declared not to be illegal or in restraint of trade.<footnote><footnote.reference>96</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I05GWMN"</f_field>GBL &s;§340(3).Research ReferencesExemption of cooperatives from state antimonopoly laws, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04A9CJ"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Trade Regulation &s;§23.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48">
<para.text>
The state laws relating to the restraint and prevention of monopolies do not apply to cooperative associations, corporate or otherwise, of farmers, gardeners, or dairymen, including livestock farmers and fruit growers, or to contracts, agreements, or arrangements made by such associations.<footnote><footnote.reference>97</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04D2HF"</f_field>GBL &s;§340(3).Research ReferencesExemption of cooperatives from state antimonopoly laws, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FVMB"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Trade Regulation &s;§23.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48">
<para.text>
Persons engaged in the production of agricultural products may act together in associations, corporate or otherwise, with or without capital stock, in collectively processing, preparing for market, handling, and marketing in interstate or foreign commerce products of persons so engaged.<footnote><footnote.reference>98</footnote.reference><footnote.body>5►<f_field>fn.fnref="5"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>See ►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04IOR7"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§110.Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04LHW3"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.</footnote.body></footnote> Such corporations and their members are further authorized to make the necessary contracts and agreements to effect these purposes.<footnote><footnote.reference>99</footnote.reference><footnote.body>6►<f_field>fn.fnref="6"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04OB0Z"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§14.</footnote.body></footnote> However, these corporations are subject to requirements that they be operated for the members' mutual benefit, that they do not deal in the products of nonmembers to an amount greater in value than the amount handled for members, that no member of the corporation be allowed more than one vote regardless of the amount of stock or membership capital he or she may own in the corporation, and that the corporations do not pay dividends on stock or membership in excess of 12&percnt;% per year.<footnote><footnote.reference>100</footnote.reference><footnote.body>7►<f_field>fn.fnref="7"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04A9CL"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§111.Research ReferencesPower of cooperatives to conduct business, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D2HH"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§4734, 4754.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48">
<para.text>
The marketing contract may provide that the corporation may sell or resell the products delivered by its members, with or without taking title to such products, and may pay over to its members the resale price or the pool price, in case of pooling of sales, after deducting all necessary selling, overhead, and other costs and expenses, including interest or distribution on stock, not exceeding 6&percnt;% per year, and any other deductions authorized by the bylaws or marketing contract.<footnote><footnote.reference>101</footnote.reference><footnote.body>8►<f_field>fn.fnref="8"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04FVMD"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(4).Research ReferencesAgricultural cooperative corporations, generally, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04A9DR"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§2930.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48">
<para.text>
The marketing agreement may fix specific sums as liquidated damages, which sums will not be regarded as penalties, payable for breach by a member or shareholder or contracting nonmember of the marketing obligation.<footnote><footnote.reference>102</footnote.reference><footnote.body>9►<f_field>fn.fnref="9"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04D2IN"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(2).Research ReferencesProvision for liquidated damages with respect to marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FVNJ"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§479478.Liquidated damage provision in marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04IOSF"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§436.</footnote.body></footnote> A provision of this type may also be placed in the certificate of incorporation or bylaws.1<footnote><footnote.reference>103</footnote.reference><footnote.body>10►<f_field>fn.fnref="10"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04LHXB"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(2).Research ReferencesProvision for liquidated damages with respect to marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04OB27"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§479478.Liquidated damage provision in marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04A9DT"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§463.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48">
<para.text>
It may be further provided that a member or shareholder will pay all costs, premiums for bonds, expenses, and fees in case the corporation recovers judgment in any action on the marketing contract.1<footnote><footnote.reference>104</footnote.reference><footnote.body>11►<f_field>fn.fnref="11"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04D2IP"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(2).Research ReferencesProvision for liquidated damages with respect to marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FVNL"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§479478.</footnote.body></footnote> A corporation is also given the right, in the event of a breach or threatened breach of a marketing contract by a member or by a contracting nonmember, to enjoin further breach of the contract and to obtain a decree of specific performance to enforce the contract.1<footnote><footnote.reference>105</footnote.reference><footnote.body>12►<f_field>fn.fnref="12"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04IOSH"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(3).Research ReferencesRight of cooperative to injunction and specific performance with respect to marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04LHXD"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§480§479.Injunction and specific performance to enforce marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04OB29"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§44.</footnote.body></footnote> Upon the filing of a verified complaint showing a breach of the marketing agreement and of a bond approved by the court, the corporation is entitled to a temporary restraining order.1<footnote><footnote.reference>106</footnote.reference><footnote.body>13►<f_field>fn.fnref="13"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|50|32:48"</f_field>►<f_field>st.ref.id="I04A9JH"</f_field>Coop. Corp. Law &s;§70(3).Research ReferencesRight of cooperative to injunction and specific performance with respect to marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04D2OD"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &s;§480§479.Injunction and specific performance to enforce marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FVT9"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§44.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
</section>
