<outline.name.block>
<designator>32:49</designator>
<name>Form drafting principles</name>
</outline.name.block>
<research.reference.block>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I09QC7W"</field>West's Key Number Digest, Agriculture &key;6</ref.text></reference.entry>
<reference.entry><ref.text>►<field>tk.ref.id="I09M4IK"</field>West's Key Number Digest, <trace.deleted>Associations &key;5</trace.deleted><trace>Associations &key;128, 129</trace></ref.text></reference.entry>
</research.reference.block>
</section.front>
<section.body>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|51|32:49">
<para.text>
To be effective, a marketing contract must satisfy such basic requirements of all contracts as competent parties who express definite assent in the form required, sufficient consideration, and a legal object or purpose.<footnote><footnote.reference>107</footnote.reference><footnote.body>1►<f_field>fn.fnref="1"</f_field>Research ReferencesValidity and binding effect of marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04FVTB"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§31.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|51|32:49">
<para.text>
A marketing contract, due to its complexity, should always be in writing and should observe formalities that are often omitted in the simpler forms of contract. Because such contracts are construed strictly, extreme care should be taken to avoid any ambiguities in the contract's provisions.<footnote><footnote.reference>108</footnote.reference><footnote.body>2►<f_field>fn.fnref="2"</f_field>Research ReferencesPower of cooperatives to enter into marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04IOY7"</f_field>N.Y. Jur. 2d, Business Relationships &ss;§§4778 to 4821.Marketing contracts, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04LI33"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &ss;§§30 to 48.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
<online.view.item>Practice Tip:</online.view.item>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|51|32:49">
<para.text>
Marketing contracts are sometimes attached to preorganization agreements in order that they may be signed by prospective members prior to incorporation of the cooperative. In such circumstances, the marketing agreement is executed contemporaneously by the prospective member with the execution of the organization agreement and as a part of the entire contract.
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|51|32:49">
<para.text>
Marketing contracts entered into prior to the formation of a producers' marketing corporation are valid and binding upon the producers as signers after the formation of the corporation.<footnote><footnote.reference>109</footnote.reference><footnote.body>3►<f_field>fn.fnref="3"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|51|32:49"</f_field>See ►<f_field>cc.ref.id="I04A9JM"</f_field>Castorland Milk & Cheese Co. v. Shantz, 179 N.Y.S. 131 (Sup 1919).</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
<online.view.item>Practice Tip:</online.view.item>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|51|32:49">
<para.text>
A cooperative marketing agreement may create either of two relationships with respect to the products to be marketed under it: (1) a relationship of buyer and seller (a sales contract); or (2) the relationship of principal and agent between the member and the association (an agency contract). The nature of the relationship and the type of contract created depends upon the intention of the parties, as evidenced by the provisions of the contract, and as viewed in the light of the articles of incorporation or charter, the bylaws, and the circumstances of the particular case, including applicable statutory provisions.<footnote><footnote.reference>110</footnote.reference><footnote.body>4►<f_field>fn.fnref="4"</f_field>►<f_field><para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|51|32:49"</f_field>See ►<f_field>cc.ref.id="I04D2OI"</f_field>Pyrke v. Brudno, 243 A.D. 493, 278 N.Y.S. 353 (3d Dep't 1935), aff'd, 269 N.Y. 652, 200 N.E. 42 (1936) (milk producers' cooperative contract to sell milk to a milk dealer was one of agency and not of purchase and sale).Research ReferencesNature of, and relationship created by, marketing agreement, ►<f_field>rc.ref.id="I04IOYA"</f_field>Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§35.</footnote.body></footnote>
</para.text>
</para>
</section.body>
