►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|52|32:50">
<para.text>
A cooperative marketing agreement may create either of two relationships with respect to the products to be marketed under it: (1) a relationship of buyer and seller (a sales contract); or (2) the relationship of principal and agent between the member and the association (an agency contract). The nature of the relationship and the type of contract created depends upon the intention of the parties, as evidenced by the provisions of the contract, and as viewed in the light of the articles of incorporation or charter, the bylaws, and the circumstances of the particular case, including applicable statutory provisions. See ►<field>cc.ref.id="I05GWE6"</field>Pyrke v. Brudno, 243 A.D. 493, 278 N.Y.S. 353 (3d Dep't 1935), aff'd, 269 N.Y. 652, 200 N.E. 42 (1936) (milk producers' cooperative contract to sell milk to a milk dealer was one of agency and not of purchase and sale). Using this checklist provision would clearly create a sales contract.
</para.text>
</para>
<research.reference.block>
<cite type="secondary"><reference.entry><ref.text>►Am. Jur. 2d, Cooperative Associations &s;§35</ref.text></reference.entry></cite>
