►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|52|32:50">
<para.text>
In general, rights under a contract involving no personal confidential relation and no exceptional personal skill or knowledge are assignable. An executory contract which is not personal in character and which can, consistent with the rights and interests of the adverse party, be sufficiently executed by the assignee, is assignable, in the absence of an agreement to the contrary. ►<field>cc.ref.id="I04A9XP"</field>Special Products Mfg., Inc. v. Douglass, 159 A.D.2d 847, 553 N.Y.S.2d 506 (3d Dep't 1990).
</para.text>
</para>
►<para ct.id="6d0bf250b92611ef8747b569df12a67d|52|32:50">
<para.text>
The courts will generally recognize and enforce a provision in a contract expressly prohibiting its assignment. ►<field>cc.ref.id="I04D32L"</field>Sacks v. Neptune Meter Co., 144 Misc. 70, 258 N.Y.S. 254 (App. Term 1932), aff'd, 238 A.D. 82, 263 N.Y.S. 462 (1st Dep't 1933).
</para.text>
</para>
